Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: While FairAlign presents a compelling vision for fairness-aware aggregation through misalignment signals, I recognize an opportunity to deepen the integration of *causal reasoning* into federated learning to distinguish between spurious and genuine fairness improvements. Existing methods like FairFed, FedLF, and mFairFL focus on gradient alignment or fairness metric aggregation but do not explicitly model the underlying causal mechanisms that generate bias across clients. In heterogeneous settings—such as hospitals with different patient demographics or banks serving distinct socioeconomic regions—observed disparities may stem from either (1) true inequity in model performance or (2) non-causal, dataset-induced correlations (e.g., zip code correlating with race due to segregation). Blindly adjusting weights based on statistical misalignment risks penalizing clients who are actually correcting such spurious biases. My new idea introduces **Causal Influence Alignment (CIA-FL)**, which leverages lightweight causal proxies to estimate whether a client’s update moves the global model toward *causally justified* fairness. By modeling group fairness through an intervention-based lens—using counterfactual fairness gradients—the framework dynamically adjusts aggregation weights not just based on statistical divergence, but on whether the local update aligns with causally fair directions derived from a shared causal graph skeleton. This approach shifts the paradigm from reactive fairness correction to proactive causal alignment, enabling FL systems to resist both statistical unfairness and structural confounding. Unlike prior work, CIA-FL does not require full access to sensitive attributes nor centralized data, yet it incorporates causal semantics via differentially private influence estimates and synthetic interventions. It also introduces a novel "fairness elasticity" metric to quantify how responsive each client is to causal fairness pressures, allowing the server to prioritize clients that actively deconfound biased representations.

